---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
    title="Data Physicalization Workshop | tcplot: Data Visualization in Minneapolis and St. Paul"
    description="Hands-on workshop translating real datasets into physical objects you can hold."
>
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto mt-8 mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">
                Upcoming: Data Physicalization Workshop — June 27th
            </h2>

            <div
                class="w-full max-w-[300px] mx-auto mb-4 rounded-lg overflow-hidden sm:float-left sm:mx-0 sm:mr-8 sm:w-[300px]"
            >
                <img
                    src="/images/legodata.gif"
                    alt="Animated clip of a data visualization built from colorful LEGO bricks"
                    class="w-full h-auto object-contain"
                />
            </div>

            <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4 italic">
                What if your next chart wasn't on a screen?
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Join <span class="font-silkscreen">tcplot</span> for a hands-on
                morning of data physicalization — translating real datasets into
                objects you can hold, turn over, and put on your desk. We'll
                explore paper, thread, beads, and the surprisingly hard question
                of what to encode when you can't reach for a library.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                We'll draw inspiration from projects like Giorgia Lupi and
                Stefanie Posavec's <em>Dear Data</em>, Nathalie Miebach's weather
                sculptures, and the broader tradition of data physicalization (<a
                    href="https://dataphys.org"
                    target="_blank"
                    rel="noopener noreferrer"
                    class="text-blue-600 hover:underline">dataphys.org</a
                >). The constraint is the point: when you can't pipe data into
                ggplot, you have to make real decisions about hierarchy,
                encoding, and what's actually worth showing.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What you'll do
            </h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Pick from a handful of small, pre-prepared datasets (<a
                            href="https://www.dnr.state.mn.us/climate/historical/daily.html"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >Twin Cities weather</a
                        >, <a
                            href="https://science.ebird.org/en/use-ebird-data/download-ebird-data-products"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >MN bird sightings</a
                        >, <a
                            href="https://opendata.minneapolismn.gov/"
                            target="_blank"
                            rel="noopener noreferrer"
                            class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
                            >library checkouts</a
                        >, a week of your own personal data, or any other data)</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        >Work solo or in pairs to translate it into a physical
                        artifact</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span>Share what you made and what surprised you</span>
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span>Leave with the object you built</span>
                </li>
            </ul>

            <div class="clear-both"></div>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                How the two hours will flow
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                A loose schedule — we'll bend it to the room. The point is that
                you walk in with a dataset and walk out with an object.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Welcome &amp; warm-up.</span
                        > Coffee, quick intros, and a gallery walk through real
                        examples — <em>Dear Data</em> postcards, Miebach's
                        weather sculptures. We'll play one tiny encoding game to
                        get the brain in physical mode.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Encoding without a library.</span
                        > A short crash course in the physical vocabulary of
                        data. On a screen you reach for <em>x</em>, <em>y</em>,
                        color, and size — in your hands you have far more to work
                        with: <strong>length</strong> (a strand of thread, a torn
                        strip of paper), <strong>count</strong> (how many beads on
                        a string), <strong>position</strong> and
                        <strong>order</strong> (near/far, stacked, sequenced),
                        <strong>color</strong> and <strong>texture</strong>
                        (smooth vs. rough, matte vs. shiny),
                        <strong>weight</strong>, <strong>height</strong>, and even
                        <strong>negative space</strong> (the gaps that say as much
                        as the marks). We'll talk about which channels the hand
                        and eye read most easily, when an encoding is honest
                        versus merely pretty, and the trade-off at the center of
                        all of this: you can only encode a few variables before an
                        object stops being legible, so choosing what to
                        <em>leave out</em> is the real craft. Then I'll turn a
                        single row of data into an object live — narrating each
                        choice — so you can see the decisions in real time before
                        you make your own.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Pick &amp; sketch.</span
                        > Choose your dataset, name the one question you want it to
                        answer, and rough out your encoding on paper
                        <em>before</em> you touch the beads.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Make.</span> The
                        heart of it — build your artifact, solo or in pairs. I'll
                        circulate with prompts when you get stuck and more
                        supplies when you get ambitious.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Show &amp; tell.</span
                        > Pass your object around the table. Tell us what you
                        encoded, what you had to leave out, and what surprised you
                        when the data became something you could hold.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Wrap.</span> A
                        group photo of everything we made, a few pointers for
                        going further, and you take your object home.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What we'll provide
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Cardstock, embroidery thread, beads, tape, markers, making
                supplies, datasets printed and ready to go.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Ideas to get you started
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Not sure where to begin? Here are a few forms that translate data
                especially well — but treat them as springboards, not
                instructions.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-6">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Wire-and-bead jewelry.</span
                        > Thread a bracelet or necklace where each bead is a day,
                        a row, or an event — color for category, size for
                        magnitude, spacing for the gaps in between. You leave
                        wearing your data.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Altoid-tin looms.</span
                        > Notch the lip of a tin, string a warp across it, and
                        weave: let the colors of the weft rows encode one
                        variable and the bands of the warp another. A whole
                        woven dataset that snaps shut in your pocket.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Layered paper topography.</span
                        > Cut and stack cardstock contours so a value over time
                        rises into a little 3D landscape — peaks for the highs,
                        valleys for the lows, something you read with your
                        fingertips.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Hanging mobiles.</span
                        > Suspend tagged elements from thread and let the piece
                        find its own balance — arm length and height encode the
                        numbers while gravity does the comparing for you.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Punch-card strips.</span
                        > Punch holes into a ribbon of cardstock, player-piano
                        style — present or absent, more or fewer — so a week of
                        yes/no data becomes a strip you can run through your
                        hands.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What to bring
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Yourself. Optionally, a week of personal data you've been
                tracking (sleep, coffee, steps, moods, anything) or your own
                craft supplies of choice.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Who this is for
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Anyone curious about data visualization — practitioners working
                in D3, Tableau, ggplot2, Observable, or none of the above. No
                craft skills required.
            </p>

            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
                Hope to see you there!
            </p>

            <div class="flex justify-center mt-12">
                <div class="max-w-2xl w-full">
                    <div class="rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
                        <img
                            src="/images/hailmary.jpeg"
                            alt="Physical star model made of wire and beads radiating from a central point, from the movie Project Hail Mary"
                            class="w-full h-auto object-contain"
                        />
                    </div>
                    <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mt-2 text-center italic">
                        Still from <em>Project Hail Mary</em>. Dir. Phil Lord and
                        Christopher Miller. Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, 2026.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mt-16 mb-3">
                Books on the table
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                A small library will be out for you to flip through whenever you
                need a spark, a reference, or a reason to step back from the
                glue.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-5 text-gray-600 mb-6">
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Observe, Collect, Draw!</span
                    > — Giorgia Lupi &amp; Stefanie Posavec. A guided journal that
                    turns the <em>Dear Data</em> method into a workbook: track your
                    own life and hand-draw it.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: the fastest on-ramp to encoding personal
                        data by hand — exactly what you'll be doing today.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Dear Data</span> —
                    Giorgia Lupi &amp; Stefanie Posavec. A year of weekly
                    postcards in which two designers mailed each other hand-drawn
                    visualizations of their everyday lives.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: the founding text for slow, analog,
                        deeply personal data — proof that a chart can be made
                        entirely by hand and be the better for it.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Speak Data</span> —
                    Giorgia Lupi &amp; Phillip Cox. Conversations with artists,
                    scientists, thinkers, and dreamers about how we live our
                    lives in numbers, grounded in Lupi's idea of Data Humanism.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: it reframes data as something human and
                        felt rather than purely technical — the mindset behind
                        making data you can hold.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Code as Creative Medium</span
                    > — Golan Levin &amp; Tega Brain. A handbook of exercises and
                    assignments for teaching and learning creative coding and
                    generative art.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: a deep well of generative, constraint-led
                        prompts — many translate straight from screen to scissors
                        and thread.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Beautiful Evidence</span
                    > — Edward Tufte. On how evidence becomes argument:
                    sparklines, mapped pictures, and the integrity of showing
                    data honestly.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: the discipline of encoding truthfully — a
                        useful conscience when you're tempted to choose pretty
                        over honest.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Envisioning Information</span
                    > — Edward Tufte. A classic on escaping flatland: layering,
                    small multiples, and packing many dimensions into a clear
                    image.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: physical objects are inherently
                        multi-dimensional, and this is the master class in
                        managing that density without losing the reader.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >The Book of Circles</span
                    > — Manuel Lima. A visual history of circular information
                    design, from ancient diagrams to modern network graphics.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: a catalog of non-rectangular layouts to
                        steal from when a grid feels too obvious for your
                        object.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Nightingale, Issues 1–3</span
                    > — the Data Visualization Society. The society's print
                    journal, full of essays, interviews, and showcase work from
                    across the dataviz field.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: a snapshot of where the field is right now
                        — community, debates, and plenty of fresh visual
                        inspiration.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li>
                    <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                        >Value and Transformation of Corals</span
                    > — Christine &amp; Margaret Wertheim. The catalog of the
                    Crochet Coral Reef, a global craftivist project translating
                    marine ecology — and hyperbolic geometry — into crocheted
                    yarn.
                    <span class="block text-gray-500 mt-1"
                        >Why it's here: the most ambitious example of data and
                        science made physical by hand, at the scale of a movement
                        — proof of how far this practice can go.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>
